Random idea: Solve public transportation by using technology and smaller vehicles.
37 posts
Pont
Ars Legatus Legionis
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Los Gatos Mountains View
Registered: Aug 19, 2000Posts: 18208
Posted: Thu Apr 12, 2012 4:14 pm
Traditionally, public transportation has been about using large amounts of infrustructure to move large amounts of people in large vehicles on rigid routes.The obvious problems are:* large infrastructure means government spending and intelligent planning, neither of which are in great supply of late* it only works out with economies of scale, but if you scale to the necessary size and don't succeed it's a huge waste of money that prevents any further attempts at improvement for decades* rigid routes and time schedules lead to low ridership which leads to budget cuts which leads to fewer routes... downward spiral* big ass busses and trains simply aren't efficient when carrying few people* big vehicles require specialized drivers (and unions, and insurance, and maintenance)But I think we have the technology to make it better and we all already use it every day. GPS, smartphones, the internet, touch screens.The city/state has a fleet of mixed vehicles. Minivans, short buses, big buses. All eco-friendly (natural gas, EV with easily swappable batteries, fuel cells, etc.). Riders simply use a public terminal or smartphone app to request pickup location and destination. They get a list of options for wait times and price (depending on what's already headed that way), and possibly a bid from a local taxi company (revenue split with the city). Common pickup and dropoff locations (like bus depots) would be cheaper than custom ones. Making your request further in advance is cheaper, maybe. You are told what vehicle (type, human-friendly ID number) will pick you up and when.Then, the public transit authority computer automatically dispatches an appropriately sized vehicle for an optimized route. Simple statistics guarantee that the big routes will sill be served by big vehicles, but now they'll be mostly full all the time. The vehicles obviously all have net-connected GPS that tells dispatch where they are and lets dispatch reroute the vehicle en route. Smaller vehicles serving smaller routes are obviously not quite as efficient, but they make the overall system much more viable for people who want to give up their cars (or second car).Data mining will allow further efficiency, since you can seasonally mothball parts of your fleet or trade vehicles to other cities dynamically.
