Pont wrote:The obvious problems are:* large infrastructure means government spending and intelligent planning, neither of which are in great supply of lateA "fleet of mixed vehicles" with various "eco-friendly" refueling methods, all answering to a central computer, with support for numerous smartphones and kiosks all around the city, sounds like larger infrastructure to me than a bunch of identical buses on static routes.Quote:* it only works out with economies of scale, but if you scale to the necessary size and don't succeed it's a huge waste of money that prevents any further attempts at improvement for decadesSee above.Quote:* rigid routes and time schedules lead to low ridership which leads to budget cuts which leads to fewer routes... downward spiralWhy do you think rigid routes and times cause low ridership? Those very things offer consistency which increase confidence in the service. Quote:* big ass busses and trains simply aren't efficient when carrying few peopleBut they are still useful for paying customers. Efficiency is but one goal, it is not mass transit's reason for being.Quote:* big vehicles require specialized drivers (and unions, and insurance, and maintenance)Small vehicles carrying passengers from the public would require the same.People don't ride the bus unless they have to because you need to wait for the bus, you can't just go whenever you want. Oh, and on the way, you have no privacy or comfort. Mass transit works well in very large cities when driving and parking is more trouble/costly than mass transit, and it works for mid-sized cities for those who can't afford cars. I think you want more people to use public transportation in mid-sized cities. I think you want me to save money(?) and travel more eco-friendly(?) than I do now with my own car. Show me how public transportation would be better than owning my own car, in such a location. Sell me on it. If your system, as you described it, was completely operational today, I'd still drive my own car.
