Posted: Fri Apr 13, 2012 1:34 am
Even if such a system could be optimised on the fly to a degree that made it more efficient than static routes (a highly questionable assumption), it's going to be wildly inconsistent for users of the service.A static route and fixed schedule allows people to make very confident predictions about how long their travel will take. If I'm at the train station by 8:00, I will be at the exit point by 8:25.Now consider a dynamic route. I can no longer predict whether the shuttle bus will be at my door at 7:45 or at 8:05. Will the trip take 20 minutes or 40? On average, it might result in less time spent in transit, but averages aren't terribly useful to me when I need to be at work by 9:00am. If I can't be certain whether the trip (including waiting time) will be 20 minutes or 60 minutes, I have to allow for 60 minutes every time.If your primary concern is fuel efficiency rather than user experience, well, I think it's extraordinarily unlikely that any degree of route optimisation could possibly outweigh the efficiency cost of using more small vehicles over few large vehicles.
