Not to get too deep, but I think part of the problem is that from the perspective of cities with adequate public transportation, this seems unnecessary. Coming from a city with completely inadequate public transportation, it makes more sense as a possible alternative, except that the cost of 'taxi' service is so ridiculous as to make it's use impractical for those who actually need public transit.As for the pipe-dream of zoning some everyone can walk/bike to work/store/home, the problem with that concept is that you're trying to transform large cities, with their specialized areas that focus on certain aspects and have improvements geared directly toward those assets (like industrial parks) and trying to transform them all into miniaturized self-sufficient towns. It doesn't work well that way.What we really need is residential mobility, so that people can afford to move to places that are more adequate to their needs as their jobs and purchasing needs change. Rather than trying to shoehorn everything into one place for everyone so that you remove the need for transit, better to allow people to financially move so that they can reduce the problems the lack of door-to-door transit can cause. Centralize work/shopping in particular areas for easy public transit, and residential areas situated between them along the routes with a variety of options as far as cost so that poor people can afford to live on the bus lines that take them to their new job and new grocery store and new school and...The only way a zoning solution works to really make any change is if we start using a planned economy where people are assigned jobs and the like. Otherwise, while work might be available in your neighborhood, your actual place of employment likely isn't there, and you can't afford to move to where it is.-----------------------Public transit in my city is centered around spokes out from the central hub of going downtown. Downtown is a hub of work, but the problem is that the people who generally work there don't live there, they live in the suburbs, and they aren't poor and don't need public transit. The poor who do need it generally can't get it in anything resembling a timely manner so that they can arrive at their work. And if they live downtown? There isn't adequate shopping for basic needs. There's one overpriced grocery store to cover the entire area, and it has limited selections. I can't really blame it; space downtown is expensive and they can't afford to stock as much or as cheaply as the big chains can, and the big chains have no interest in serving downtown, as the people with money live in the suburbs or can easily drive out to the suburbs to buy. Again, it all disadvantages the poor, who's lack of money leads to a lack of a voice as far as what they need.Indianapolis is nothing like London in size or population, but it also doesn't have anything like an adequate public transit system, and there's no real way a London or NYC style subway system here would be self-supporting. The population isn't dense enough to justify the expense, and parking isn't at that much of a premium such that the middle class and upper class workers would really go for public transit over their own private transit.Massive public funding could put up something like an elevated train, but to be self-sufficient it'd have to mostly service the population areas where people had money, and that's precisely where it's least needed.
