Syonyk wrote:Have you either ridden public transit much, or driven it?The current system is hard enough for a lot of people...I'm not entirely sure what problem you're trying to solve, but point to point public transit is *vastly* less efficient than the current "big busses on fixed routes" approach. Fraction of the passengers.I've driven both. As volume picked up, the door to door busses were nearly completely replaced by "big busses on fixed routes." The number of people carried went up, and generally we still got people where they wanted to go.I know it certainly depends on location, but yes... I use public transportation every day, unless I elect to walk instead. I don't own a car since my divorce. Public transportation CAN be a little frustrating, but so can driving. Having said all of that, I chose to live where I knew I had good options. I have the option of a shuttle from my apt. building to the metro, a bus route that runs past the property, and two major bus routes within a mile walk in either direction. All busses run to the nearest metro station, approx 2 miles away. From there, I can get almost anywhere I need to go in this metro area of 6 million people. Yes, it takes more time and planning than driving, but I think the costs and availability are well matched here in the DC area. If I really need more convinience/speed, I have options of a taxi or zip car. Bus services in the DC area are *reasonably* well run in my opinion. If ridership on a route drops low enough to be unsustainable, they simply cut back on the# of trips on that route. (eg - during rush hour, there is a bus that passes next to my building ever 20 min. As rush hour tapers off, bus service drops to every 45 min, then there are no buses during the middle of the day on that route, next bus is at approx. 4pm. and run every 30 min, then every 20 through rush hour. At least here in DC, the system in place seems perfectly adequate *to me* and systems requiring greater infrastructure (metro/subway) are in development to cover a wider area as well, with 2 more metro line routes in the planning/construction stages at this time.[just a quick edit. For those who would argue that my case is special because I live in an urban center... well, I don't live TOO far from downtown, but I had 3 deer cross the road along the bus route Wednesday afternoon as I got home... so this isn't a "everyone move to the center of town" solution, this is intelligent management of fixed routes, balancing coverage and schedules.]
