Hangfire wrote:Vampyre wrote:As for the pipe-dream of zoning some everyone can walk/bike to work/store/home, the problem with that concept is that you're trying to transform large cities, with their specialized areas that focus on certain aspects and have improvements geared directly toward those assets (like industrial parks) and trying to transform them all into miniaturized self-sufficient towns. It doesn't work well that way.The only way a zoning solution works to really make any change is if we start using a planned economy where people are assigned jobs and the like. Otherwise, while work might be available in your neighborhood, your actual place of employment likely isn't there, and you can't afford to move to where it is.I'd counter that argument with the example of Detroit and yet again allowing big corporations to make the planning decisions. Sure you may not be able to reap the benefits right now but on the other hand you don't get decrepit cess pits like Detroit falling apart either, becoming entirely bankrupt etc etc and then allowing the Big corporations to yet again build walled enclaves that only benefit a minority of the population. I disagree that a planned economy is required in that situation. If you zone the thing intelligently it'll be self sustaining. But that requires an impartial governmental apparatus, something that seems entirely impossible to achieve with the American political machine.Also, profit? These are essential government services in providing transportation infrastructure. The idea isn't about turning a profit it's about enabling the economy to grow.You're missing my point. Aiming public transit at the problems of the middle class is a waste of time. Local governments don't want to get into the public-transit infrastructure game because if they were self-sufficient (that does not imply profit) they'd already exist. The problem is that it's a massive outlay of capital to construct services where the only real need for them is by people who can't afford those services anyway. So, the public would have to pay out a massive amount of money to construct these train systems, and then continue to pay to keep them running, all so the underclass who can't afford them can get adequate public transit.And let me be frank, I support paying taxes for better public transit. I wouldn't, and couldn't, use it, but I still support it. I think it's a big part of what keeps poor people in my area poor. They can't easily get to work, or less expensive food, or anything else. They're essentially trapped near where they are, or if they can get to one of the few remaining bus lines in my area, they can get to one of the places those buses will take them if they invest a bit of money and a giant amount of their own time. Why? Because the bus system here is generally used only by the poor, and it can't maintain itself without public tax money, and no one but me, evidently, wants to pay that.Rezoning? The first problem with that is that as a solution it ignores reality, that things already exist and have a momentum for staying where they are because of the cost of relocating. It also ignores the problem that businesses don't want to relocate into poor neighborhoods where the people don't have enough money to buy the goods they're trying to sell, and the crime is higher so the costs of doing business are higher. That means tax reductions/payments to get businesses to move into these areas. On top of that, it means a massive amount of shuffling and rebuilding, which means more taxes. Then, it doesn't actually solve the problem; people who already have jobs likely won't live near where they work, and the cost of moving to there can be prohibative, so they STILL need adequate transit. The population density isn't big enough to make public transit self-sufficient or efficient, because it has to cover too much area for too few riders, and parking isn't as difficult to obtain for private transit.In short, the costs associated with changing, and the lack of costs associated with not changing, mean that rezoning as a solution will NEVER happen. It doesn't even adequately solve the issue at hand, unless your only concern is environmental. I'm much more concerned about making it possible for poor people to obtain and retain work and remain in their communities with their family and friends than I am in the level of smog. The smog thing would be nice, and in the end it may be enough to get something done IF the cost of land continues to increase to the point where parking becomes too expensive in highly desirable areas AND IF the population density increases enough that riders payments can adequately maintain the system without making it prohibitively expensive. That's a lot of ifs.Indianapolis isn't a small city. It's also not a dense city. Detroit's problems are much bigger than can be laid at the feet of car manufacturers. Short of using governmental force to make something like what you're describing occur, it just won't work because there are too many incentives to resist it from the people who actually have the money to make something happen.Frankly, until you can frame your solution in such a way that the natural economic forces make it viable AND it addresses the problem of the poor and their transportation/employment needs, you're wasting your time.
