Posted: Fri Apr 13, 2012 12:29 pm
Yes, I should clarify that I'm talking about public transit in the USA, not the world in general. We're a car based society and we have a real problem investing in public transit.Quote:A "fleet of mixed vehicles" with various "eco-friendly" refueling methods, all answering to a central computer, with support for numerous smartphones and kiosks all around the city, sounds like larger infrastructure to me than a bunch of identical buses on static routes.But it can start small and grow as it needs. There's very little pre-building, compared to a full bus system. The software part of it would be amortized among all the cities using it. You don't have to start with custom eco-friendly vehicles. You can start with an off-the-shelf minivan and put the GPS/communication console in it.Quote:But they are still useful for paying customers. Efficiency is but one goal, it is not mass transit's reason for being.The goal would be to use big busses whenever possible. Just instead of pre-planning what the rigid bus routes are a year/month in advance, you can use software algorithms to guarantee that you only use big busses on routes that need big busses. The routes that always need big busses? They'll always use big busses.The popular routes with high ridership will not change. They're the successful part of current public transit.Quote:Now consider a dynamic route. I can no longer predict whether the shuttle bus will be at my door at 7:45 or at 8:05. Will the trip take 20 minutes or 40? On average, it might result in less time spent in transit, but averages aren't terribly useful to me when I need to be at work by 9:00am.In my experience with tradional busses, you still can't guarantee timelyness or trip time very well, once you get past the popular every-ten-minutes bus routes.Quote:Looks like you want all the benefits of owning a car without having to own a car. Get over it, public transport is a trade off. Deal. I'm saying we can make it less of a tradeoff, with the goal of making it easier for more people to switch to using primarily public transit.The rest of your (Hangfire's) points are all basically repeating "wow, public transit and public works in the US is kinda disfunctional." Yeah. I agree. In the US, public transit is at constant odds with the car society and local governments are mostly all looking at cutting government services wherever they can. Cutting public transit routes with low ridership is, politically, much easier than cutting school funding, police, and fire. Then, when that route is cut, there is now no way to get from point A to B when you need to, so you buy a car. Now, you have a car you're paying for anyways, so why bother with public transit at all. Which pushes down ridership on more routes. Those routes get cut. Lather, rinse, repeat.Sometimes, accepting a little inefficiency to make a system more flexible makes the whole system more healthy.I'm not suggesting a free public taxi service that will pick you up and drop you off anywhere, any time. Just something in between that and the current system of completely rigid routes and time schedules. Previous point-to-point systems have a lot of inefficiency simply because call-in and dispatch are manually operated. An automated system could lump multiple people together in a shared route along an efficient path (in theory).The touchscreen kiosks I mentioned would just be a way for people without smartphones to enter pickup and delivery destinations. Much of the time on the traditional routes, this would just be a way for the system to tell them "there is already a bus on the way that will be at $BusStop in 10 minutes". If you want to save money, you could potentially just integrate with existing touch screen systems in ATMs, Lotto machines, movie theaters, etc. But that requires a pretty impressive level of public/private coordination....and if they ever get self-driving cars, a system like this would be pretty useful.Quote:If he'd read any of the thousands of studies, news reports, background etc etc about it I wouldn't have had a problem, but he didn't. Instead, out of sheer wilful ignorance and deliberate stupidity he proposed a solution looking for a non-existent problem, so I did have a problem with it. I did say "Random idea", not "I'm a super genious and you all should bow down to my solution." No need to be an ass.
